<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate voltage drop?", answer: "For single-phase circuits, voltage drop = 2 × length × current × resistance / 1000, where length is one-way feet, current is in amps, and resistance is ohms per 1000 ft from NEC Chapter 9 Table 8. Three-phase uses √3 instead of 2. Divide the result by the source voltage to get the percentage drop." },
  { question: "What is the NEC limit on voltage drop?", answer: "NEC 210.19(A) Informational Note 4 recommends a maximum 3% drop on branch circuits and 5% total drop on feeders plus branches combined. These are guidelines, not strict requirements, but most jurisdictions and utilities enforce them." },
  { question: "Why does voltage drop matter?", answer: "Excessive drop reduces motor torque, dims lights, overheats equipment, and wastes energy as heat in the wire. Motors running at reduced voltage draw more current to maintain power, which shortens their life and can trip breakers. Sensitive electronics may reset or malfunction below 5% drop." },
  { question: "When do I need to upsize wire for voltage drop?", answer: "Common cases: long branch circuits (over ~100 ft for 120 V), subpanels to detached buildings, motor feeders, EV chargers in remote garages, well pumps, and any circuit where calculated drop exceeds 3%. Going up one AWG size typically cuts drop by 20-30%." },
  { question: "Is copper or aluminum better for long runs?", answer: "Copper has about 60% the resistance of aluminum per AWG, so shorter runs typically use copper. For very long runs aluminum can be cost-effective at a larger size; for example, a 2/0 aluminum feeder may replace a 1 AWG copper feeder with similar drop at lower cost. Always use antioxidant paste on aluminum terminations." }
]) %>

